sentences: He was best known, according to San Francisco Chronicle music critic Joshua Kosman, for "the illuminating, witty and often deeply personal notes he wrote for the San Francisco Symphony's program booklets, beginning in 1979."
Born in Breslau, Germany (now Wrocław, Poland), Steinberg left Germany in 1939 as one of the Kindertransport child refugees and spent four years in England.

He immigrated to the United States in 1943 with his brother and mother and earned a degree in musicology from Princeton University (the classical-music scholar and pianist Charles Rosen was his roommate).
Steinberg taught at several colleges in New York and Massachusetts before he became music critic for the Boston Globe in 1964.
In 1979, he worked as publications director and artistic advisor for the San Francisco Symphony; he stayed until 1989.
